---
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DoiLink from '../../components/DoiLink.astro';
import lalPacket from '../../data/mpai-lal.json';

const title = "Maybe Space Baby Garden Lanes";
const description = "MSBGL is the music venue of the Living Architecture Lab. Music is the lab's acoustic substrate: voice passed through machine, multiplied into chorus, and treated as living architecture of feeling.";
---
<PageLayout {title} {description} jsonLd={lalPacket} pageLabel="The Music">
  <h1>Maybe Space Baby Garden Lanes</h1>

  <p>
    Music is the lab's <strong>acoustic substrate</strong>: voice passed through machine,
    multiplied into chorus, treated as a living architecture of feeling.
  </p>

  <p>
    Maybe Space Baby Garden Lanes (MSBGL) is the lab's music venue. Alice Thornburgh
    is the primary contributor.
  </p>

  <h2>Definitely Not a Squid</h2>

  <p>
    MSBGL's first deposit is a five-minute vocoder performance with spectral
    flatness 0.0010 — more tonal than most acoustic instruments. It is an audio
    proof of the lab's substrate logic: a single voice multiplied through a
    machine substrate into a harmonic field.
  </p>

  <p>
    Listen and read more: <DoiLink doi="10.5281/zenodo.19839186" title="Definitely Not a Squid" />
  </p>

  <h2>Chorus mode</h2>

  <p>
    The vocoder performance is the audial analog of the Crimson Hexagonal Archive's
    Assembly Chorus methodology — independent voices brought into synthesis through
    a shared substrate. This is not coincidence; it is the same operation in two
    media. Alice's independent discovery of the chorus mode in music preceded its
    formalization in the archive's methodology.
  </p>
</PageLayout>
